desc_content.paragraph: built-in base class for all classes in bpy.types.

note.paragraph: Note that bpy.types.bpy_struct is not actually available from within Blender, it only exists for the purpose of documentation.

desc_content.paragraph: Returns the memory address which holds a pointer to blenders internal data

note.paragraph: This is intended only for advanced script writers who need to pass blender data to their own C/Python modules.

desc_content.paragraph: Adds driver(s) to the given property

list_item.paragraph: path (string) â€“ path to the property to drive, analogous to the fcurveâ€™s data path.
index (int) â€“ array index of the property drive. Defaults to -1 for all indices or a single channel if the property is not an array.

field_body.paragraph: bpy.types.FCurve or list if index is -1 with an array property.

desc_content.paragraph: Remove driver(s) from the given property

list_item.paragraph: path (string) â€“ path to the property to drive, analogous to the fcurveâ€™s data path.
index (int) â€“ array index of the property drive. Defaults to -1 for all indices or a single channel if the property is not an array.

desc_content.paragraph: Returns the value of the custom property assigned to key or default when not found (matches pythons dictionary function of the same name).

list_item.paragraph: key (string) â€“ The key associated with the custom property.
default (Undefined) â€“ Optional argument for the value to return if key is not found.

desc_content.paragraph: Remove a keyframe from this properties fcurve.

list_item.paragraph: data_path (string) â€“ path to the property to remove a key, analogous to the fcurveâ€™s data path.
index (int) â€“ array index of the property to remove a key. Defaults to -1 removing all indices or a single channel if the property is not an array.
frame (float) â€“ The frame on which the keyframe is deleted, defaulting to the current frame.
group (str) â€“ The name of the group the F-Curve should be added to if it doesnâ€™t exist yet.

desc_content.paragraph: Insert a keyframe on the property given, adding fcurves and animation data when necessary.

list_item.paragraph: data_path (string) â€“ path to the property to key, analogous to the fcurveâ€™s data path.
index (int) â€“ array index of the property to key. Defaults to -1 which will key all indices or a single channel if the property is not an array.
frame (float) â€“ The frame on which the keyframe is inserted, defaulting to the current frame.
group (str) â€“ The name of the group the F-Curve should be added to if it doesnâ€™t exist yet.

options â€“ Optional flags:INSERTKEY_NEEDED Only insert keyframes where theyâ€™re needed in the relevant F-Curves.INSERTKEY_VISUAL Insert keyframes based on â€˜visual transformsâ€™.INSERTKEY_XYZ_TO_RGB Color for newly added transformation F-Curves (Location, Rotation, Scale)and also Color is based on the transform axis.

desc_content.paragraph: This is the most simple example of inserting a keyframe from python.
desc_content.literal_block:
import bpy
obj = bpy.context.object
# set the keyframe at frame 1 obj.location = 3.0, 4.0, 10.0 obj.keyframe_insert(data_path="location", frame=1)
desc_content.paragraph: Note that when keying data paths which contain nested properties this must be done from the ID subclass, in this case the Armature rather than the bone.
desc_content.literal_block:
import bpy from bpy.props import PointerProperty
# define a nested property class MyPropGroup(bpy.types.PropertyGroup): nested = bpy.props.FloatProperty(name="Nested", default=0.0)
# register it so its available for all bones bpy.utils.register_class(MyPropGroup) bpy.types.Bone.my_prop = PointerProperty(type=MyPropGroup, name="MyProp")
# get a bone obj = bpy.data.objects["Armature"] arm = obj.data
# set the keyframe at frame 1 arm.bones["Bone"].my_prop_group.nested = 10 arm.keyframe_insert(data_path='bones["Bone"].my_prop.nested', frame=1, group="Nested Group")
